{"abstract": "ASML Holding, maker of the most expensive machines in chip fabrication, said fourth-quarter profit quadrupled on demand for semiconductors used in iPod music devices and mobile phones. {"abstract": "Amazon.com is quietly building a library of exclusive online content to rival Netflix, the champion of streaming media; cat videos are used to sell things rather than simply distract; and a Japanese television show captures the angst of a major lithium-ion battery manufacturer.", "web_url": "https://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/12/the-breakfast-meeting-amazon-challenges-netflix-and-an-advertiser-turns-to-cat-videos/", "snippet": "Amazon.com is quietly building a library of exclusive online content to rival Netflix, the champion of streaming media; cat videos are used to sell things rather than simply distract; and a Japanese television show captures the angst of a major li...", "lead_paragraph": "Amazon.com is slowly building a library of streaming television shows and movies to rival that of Netflix, much to the satisfaction of media companies like Time Warner and CBS, Brian Stelter writes. Amazon will not unveil its own original shows until fall at the earliest, but it has spent hundreds of millions of dollars to win exclusive Web rights on shows for its Amazon Prime streaming service, like \u201cDownton Abbey\u201d from PBS and \u201cFalling Skies\u201d from TNT. Amazon is a long way from matching Netflix in terms of TV and movie selection, but parts of the media business already see the company as Pepsi to Netflix\u2019s Coke. Other companies, including Google, Sony, Intel and a new venture by Redbox and Verizon, are scrambling for a Snapple or Red Bull.", "source": "The New York Times", "multimedia": [], "headline": {"main": "The Breakfast Meeting: Amazon Challenges Netflix, and an Advertiser Turns to Cat Videos", "kicker": "Media Decoder", "content_kicker": null, "print_headline": "", "name": null, "seo": null, "sub": null}, "keywords": [], "pub_date": "2013-02-12T13:26:52+0000", "document_type": "article", "news_desk": "", "section_name": "Business Day", "subsection_name": "Media", "byline": {"original": "By Daniel E. {"abstract": "Nielsen expands its ratings to include people who watch TV via the Internet; one last look at where the contenders stand before the Oscars are handed out; and an ad campaign tries to universalize sake.", "web_url": "https://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/22/the-breakfast-meeting-nielsen-adds-web-linked-tvs-to-ratings-and-a-tight-oscar-races-final-recap/", "snippet": "Nielsen expands its ratings to include people who watch TV via the Internet; one last look at where the contenders stand before the Oscars are handed out; and an ad campaign tries to universalize sake.", "lead_paragraph": "Nielsen announced that its TV ratings would begin including viewers who watch shows on Internet-connected TVs, and pledged to include those who use iPads or other mobile devices in the future, Brian Stelter writes. Although the percentage of TV viewers who rely on the Internet exclusively is negligible, television executives are concerned that many consumers are being missed regularly. Most Internet viewings of TV shows are not counted in Nielsen\u2019s ratings because they are shown without commercials or with different commercials than when they aired on television \u2014 and new streaming services, like Aereo and one in the works from Intel, stream shows and ads without cable. The expanded ratings will allow executives to count customers that these types of services may steal away from cable.", "source": "The New York Times", "multimedia": [], "headline": {"main": "The Breakfast Meeting: Nielsen Adds Web-Linked TVs to Ratings, and a Tight Oscar Race\u2019s Final Recap", "kicker": "Media Decoder", "content_kicker": null, "print_headline": "", "name": null, "seo": null, "sub": null}, "keywords": [], "pub_date": "2013-02-22T13:52:52+0000", "document_type": "article", "news_desk": "", "section_name": "Business Day", "subsection_name": "Media", "byline": {"original": "By Daniel E. {"abstract": "JPMorgan Chase and Wells Fargo, set to report fourth-quarter results on Tuesday, will kick off a flurry of bank earnings, and Intel will post its fourth-quarter results.", "web_url": "https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/13/business/economic-reports-for-the-week-of-jan-13.html", "snippet": "JPMorgan Chase and Wells Fargo, set to report fourth-quarter results on Tuesday, will kick off a flurry of bank earnings, and Intel will post its fourth-quarter results.", "lead_paragraph": "BANK EARNINGS JPMorgan Chase and Wells Fargo, set to report fourth-quarter results on Tuesday, will kick off a flurry of bank earnings. The banking giants, analysts say, will most likely face sluggish demand from borrowers whose appetite for refinancing has been sapped by rising rates. For JPMorgan Chase, the nation\u2019s largest bank, the quarterly report comes after a string of costly government settlements, prompting analysts to predict that high legal costs could hamper profit. All told, JPMorgan will have paid some $20 billion to resolve government investigations in the last 12 months alone.
